[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 4, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "a63de8e9153032905e39024e7fea49532b85777dd53edc7aae374a65d2af9969"]
[Category "Defense"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "defense/defensive_signals"]
[Student "E"]
{[showcards W:SK N:S9]

You are North. The bidding has been as shown. Partner led the \SA, dummy played the \S2 and you signal with your \ST. South next plays the \SQ and you drop the \S4, completing your doubleton signal. South then plays the \SK and it turns out you don't have to ruff after all. So what are you going to play?

Play the \C9.

This should be a clear enough signal for South to play a \C to your \CA next.

An alternate play, just as good, would be for you to ruff the good \SQ and play the \CA yourself.

If you don't get your \C trick at trick 4 you will never get it. East will discard his \CK on West's extra \D winner.}
[Play "W"]SA

